Head suboval (
Fig. 152
), about as long as wide (L/W=0.93–1.07, M=0.98), slightly widened behind eyes, with two pairs of interocular setae. Temples about as long as eyes (LT/LE=0.89–1.17, M=1.02). Dorsal side of head shining, without micropunctures. Only sparse pale grey pubescence behind eyes. Four postocular setae visible on each side, additional seta on hind margin of eye absent. Mandibles each with one large tooth (
Fig. 153
). Maxillary palpi with terminal segment wide and quite long, pubescent, asymmetric, slightly wider and markedly longer than glabrous penultimate segment which is triangular (
Fig. 154
). First segment of antenna nearly as long as next four; segments 1 to 5 elongate, segment 5 slightly longer than wide (R=1.09–1.58, M=1.28), segment 6 about as long as wide, segments 7–9 transverse, segment 10 markedly transverse (R=0.66–0.88, M=0.74).

Pronotum (
Fig. 152
) markedly transverse (W/L=1.13–1.20, M=1.17), markedly widened behind with sides moderately rounded, widest in basal half, shining, without micropunctures. One pair of dorsal setae and one pair of lateral setae. Marginal setae short. Elytra markedly transverse (R=1.16–1.67, M=1.45) with short, pale, but not shining pubescence arising from dense aspirate punctures. Apical fringe of bristles slightly longer than pubescence on other parts of the elytra. Abdominal tergites with short, moderately dense pubescence, about as fine and slightly sparser than on elytra.

Meso- and metatarsi with short empodial setae, shorter than claws (similar as in 
Figs. 87, 88
).

Male (n=5). Sternite 9 very long and narrow (
Figs. 163
), tergite 10 markedly narrowed posteriorly with moderately long apical setae. (
Fig. 162
). Aedeagus (
Figs. 155–161
) 
0.94–1.08 mm
long (M = 
1.02 mm
). Parameres bilobed, lobes markedly separated, sensory pegs confusedly arranged in posterior quarter (
Fig. 161
). Median lobe slightly overreaching paramere, apex widely rounded (
Figs. 157–159
, 
161
).
